s how world literature is coded and recoded as literary works find new homes on faraway bookshelves. Mani argues that the proliferation of world literature in a society is the function of a nation's relationship with print culture-a Faustian pact with books. Moving from early Orientalist collections, to the Nazi magazine Weltliteratur, to the European Digital Library, Mani reveals the political foundations for a history of world literature that is at once a philosophical ideal, a process of exchange, a mode of reading, and a system of classification.Shifting current scholarship's focus from the academic to the general reader, from the university to the public sphere, Recoding World Literature argues that world literature is culturally determined, historically conditioned, and politically charged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aBooksxHistory. 0aBooks. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literature. 0aLiterature and globalization. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature. 4aLibrary & Information Science. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aBibliomigrancy.  aBook Series.  aEuropean Digital Library.  aHermann Hesse.  aJohann Wolfgang von Goethe.  aKarl Marx.  aNational Socialism.  aOrientalism.  aTranslation.  aWorld Literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107290160 cprintz978082327340940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823273430?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823273430zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docum